.TH _PRINTF 3 "March 2026" "Holberton School" "Printf Manual"

.SH NAME
_printf \- print formatted output


.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.sp
.B int _printf(const char *format, ...);


.SH DESCRIPTION
The _printf function prints text to the screen.
It takes a format string and converts special codes into values.
.sp
Returns the number of characters printed.
Returns -1 if the format string is NULL.


.SH FORMAT CODES
These special codes tell _printf what to print:
.TP
.B %c
Print one character.
.TP
.B %s
Print a string (text).
If the string is NULL, prints "(null)".
.TP
.B %d
Print a whole number.
.TP
.B %i
Print a whole number (same as %d).
.TP
.B %%
Print the % symbol.


.SH RETURN VALUE
Returns how many characters were printed.
Returns -1 if format is NULL or empty.


.SH EXAMPLES

Print text:
.nf
_printf("Hello World\\n");
.fi
.sp

Print with a string:
.nf
_printf("My name is %s\\n", "Alberto");
.fi
.sp

Print with a number:
.nf
_printf("I have %d apples\\n", 5);
.fi
.sp

Print a character:
.nf
_printf("Letter: %c\\n", 'A');
.fi
.sp

Print a percent sign:
.nf
_printf("Discount: 50%%\\n");
.fi


.SH NOTES
Unknown format codes will print the % and the code.
Does not support fancy options like width or decimals.


.SH BUGS
Does not support %f for decimal numbers.
Does not support width or precision specifiers.
Does not support flag modifiers like +, -, 0.

